Reference-contexts: INTRODUCTION EGRET on the Compton Gamma-Ray Observatory observed gamma-rays up to 20 GeV over an hour after the beginning of the gamma-ray burst on 12 February 1997 <ref> [1] </ref>. This burst has the highest fluence as recorded by BATSE within EGRET's field of view. Other weaker bursts have also been detected by EGRET. Three others have significant emission within the time interval that the sub-MeV emission was detected. <p> Essentially all charged particles are rejected by a combination of the anticoincidence shield, the time-of-flight directional trigger, and the unique signature of pair production in the tracking detector. BURSTS DETECTED &gt; 30 MEV The 4 bursts which are detected simultaneous with the sub-MeV emission are GRB940217 <ref> [1] </ref>, GRB910503 [3,4], GRB930131 [5,4], and GRB940301 [6]. These bursts are listed in order of decreasing significance of the &gt; 30 MeV emission being of longer duration than the emission detected by BATSE [7].
